      <hedline>
        <hl1>Will Lawsuits Alone Stop Acid Rain?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Timothy J Burke (Adirondack Council) says Federal legislation could stop acid rain caused by coal-fired power plants faster and more completely than Federal lawsuits (Nov 4 article); drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It was wonderful to see that the Clinton Administration has instructed Attorney General Janet Reno to take legal action against 32 coal-fired power plants that appear to be violating the Clean Air Act (front page, Nov. 4).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It was wonderful to see that the Clinton Administration has instructed Attorney General Janet Reno to take legal action against 32 coal-fired power plants that appear to be violating the Clean Air Act (front page, Nov. 4).</p>
        <p>But we should not assume that this lawsuit will stop acid rain. Carol M. Browner, administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency, estimates that the suit could cause the affected plants to reduce sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide pollution by about 15 percent.</p>
        <p>But we need cuts of 50 percent in sulfur and 70 percent in nitrogen to stop the damage.</p>
        <p>This suit is the latest in a series of legal challenges that could take years to sort out. Congress can save the courts and the taxpayers a lot of time and money by passing new legislation.</p>
        <p>TIMOTHY J. BURKE  Exec. Dir., Adirondack Council  Elizabethtown, N.Y., Nov. 4, 1999</p>
      </block>
